\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
A genetic similarity measure for identifying fine-scale population stratificatio
n and cryptic relatedness
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
author[1]{Daniel Schlauch} 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
author[1]{Christoph Lange}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
affil[1]{Department of Biostatistics and Computational Biology, Dana-Farber
 Cancer Institute and Department of Biostatistics, Harvard TH Chan School
 of Public Health, Boston, MA 02115}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
The improving quality and falling costs of next-generation sequencing has
 allowed for vast increases in availability of these data.
 With this increased abundance comes a new ability to investigate population
 structure with previously unattainable precision.
 In addition to the anthroplogical value, properly accounting for confounding
 in GWAS, particularly for rare variants, is of meaningful importance.
 [More about rare variants, recent migration, relatedness, etc...]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The impact of confounding due to population structure and cryptic relatedness
 is well established 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{ptak2002evidence, pritchard2000association, roeder2009searching}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Many approaches are utilized to address this concept at the analysis level,
 such as PCA
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{price2006principal,price2010new}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, mixed models 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{listgarten2012improved,zhou2012genome,yang2014advantages,kang2010variance}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, etc.
 or at the data collection level by limiting the scope of the study to homogeneo
us populations or matching by ancestry.
 However, as our ability to further detect structure increases with developing
 methods and technologies we find that even supposedly homogeneous populations
 contain detectable population structure that may inflate type I error particula
rly among rare variants 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{mathieson2012differential}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, the presence on cryptic relatedness presents further potential
 for confounding in GWAS, increasing both type I and type II errors 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{voight2005confounding, sun2012identifying,li2014relationship}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Much of the structure identifcation improvement can be attributed to our
 ability to identify rare alleles.
 Rare alleles may be exploited due to the fact that they are more likely
 to have arisen recently and thus a superior approach towards separating
 populations that have recently separated
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{mathieson2014demography}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, very low allele frequencies are more unstable than higher
 allele frequency, either becoming fixed at zero or becoming more common
 with high probability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study we present a genetic similarity measure that is designed to
 separate individuals with recent common ancestry.
 Our measure has clearly defined properties which can be used to test for
 homogeneity in a population and in particular identify individuals who
 are likely be related in a study population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Exploiting the relative value of rare alleles is fundamental to our method,
 which uses an intuitive, computationally straightforward approach towards
 identfying similarity between two individuals.
 Effectively, we give a larger weight to a genotype which is common to two
 individuals if the allele frequency is low among the rest of the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 individuals (
\begin_inset Formula $2n$
\end_inset

 haploid genomes), with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 variants described by the genotype matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}_{2n\times N}$
\end_inset

, we define the weighted Jaccard similarity between two haploid genomes,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,j}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{i,j}=\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{N}w_{k}\mathbf{G}_{i,k}\mathbf{G}_{j,k}}{\sum_{k=1}^{N}I\left[\sum_{l=1}^{2n}\mathbf{G}_{l,k}>1\right]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{k}=\begin{cases}
\frac{{\sum_{l=1}^{2n}\mathbf{G}_{l,k} \choose 2}}{{2n \choose 2}} & \sum_{l=1}^{2n}\mathbf{G}_{l,k}>1\\
0 & \sum_{l=1}^{2n}\mathbf{G}_{l,k}\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left(s_{i,j}|\mbox{No structure}\right) & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It therefore follows from the central limit theroem that in the absence
 of populations structure, cryptic relatedness and dependence between loci
 (such as linkage disequilibrium) the distribution of the test statistic,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 is Gaussian.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{i,j}\sim N\left(1,\sigma^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is estimated by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\sigma^{2}}=\hat{Var}\left(s_{i,j}|\mbox{No structure}\right)=\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{N}\hat{p}_{k}^{2}\left(1-\hat{p}_{k}^{2}\right)w_{k,i,j}^{2}}{\left(\sum_{k=1}^{N}I\left[\sum_{l=1}^{2n}\mathbf{G}_{l,k}>1\right]\right)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This provides an easily interpreted statistical test for evaluating possible
 relatedness between individuals in a purportedly homogeous dataset of unrelated
 individuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, this measure is particularly sensitive for measuring relatedness.
 Intuitively, we can imagine two subjects which have a kinship coefficient,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

, indicating a probability of a randomly chosen allele in each person being
 identical by descent (IBD).
 For an allele which belongs to the one person, the probability of it belonging
 to the related person is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi+\left(1-\Phi\right)\times p$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the allele frequency in the population.
 We can clearly see that for rare alleles, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is small compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

, there will be a much larger relative difference in the probability of
 shared alleles among related individuals (
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi>0$
\end_inset

) compared to unrelated individuals (
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi=0$
\end_inset

).
 Given that our method weights more highly these rarer alleles, there is
 increased sensitivity to detection of relatedness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a coefficient of relatedness, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi>0$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left(s_{i,j}|\Phi,\mbox{No other structure}\right) & =\sum_{k=1}^{N}w_{k}\left(\Phi p_{k}+\left(1-\Phi\right)p_{k}^{2}\right)\\
 & >1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, in an otherwise homogeneous population of unrelated individuals
 an uncle-nephew relationship (
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi=.125$
\end_inset

), with 
\begin_inset Formula $MAF\sim Uniform\left(.01,.1\right)$
\end_inset

 we can directly calculate the expectation of their similarity statistic,
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(s_{i,j}|\Phi=.125,\mbox{No other structure}\right)\approx2.9
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This approach is easily generalized to the diploid scenario.
 A diploid similarity score, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{diploid}$
\end_inset

, is obtained by averaging each of the four pairwise haploid 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{haploid}$
\end_inset

 scores between each person's two haploid genotypes.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 individuals, 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 genotypes per loci, the similarity between individuals 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{diploid,i,j}=\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{N}\left[w_{k}\mathbf{G}_{i_{1},k}\mathbf{G}_{j_{1},k}+w_{k}\mathbf{G}_{i_{1},k}\mathbf{G}_{j_{2},k}+w_{k}\mathbf{G}_{i_{2},k}\mathbf{G}_{j_{1},k}+w_{k}\mathbf{G}_{i_{2},k}\mathbf{G}_{j_{2},k}\right]/4}{\sum_{k=1}^{2N}I\left[\sum_{l=1}^{2n}\mathbf{G}_{l,k}>1\right]}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{G}_{i_{2},k}$
\end_inset

 refers to the 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{nd}$
\end_inset

 genotype of individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 at locus 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formulation will have the same mean
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[s_{diploid,i,j}\right]=1
\]

\end_inset

and assuming independence of each individual's haploid genomes, such as
 in the absence of inbreeding,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{Var}\left(s_{diploid,i,j}|\mbox{No structure}\right)=\frac{\hat{Var}\left(s_{haploid,i,j}|\mbox{No structure}\right)}{4}
\]

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Identification of relatedness in 1000GP data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We applied our method to data from the 1000 Genomes Project 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{10002015global, 10002012integrated}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, a consortium...[].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These populations were not identified to have cryptic relatedness or had
 cryptic relatedness removed 
\series bold
[citation difficult (pptx file posted online KGP website) ftp://ftp.1000genomes.eb
i.ac.uk/vol1/ftp/phase1/analysis_results/supporting/cryptic_relation_analysis/Neme
sh_crypticrelatedness_20120213.pptx]
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phase 3 of the 1000 Genomes Project contains approximately 2504 individuals
 with a combined total of 88 million variants.
 To test our method, we sampled 80,000 variants uniformly spaced in the
 dataset in order to limit the impact of linkage disequilibrium.
 Our method was then run on each of the 26 populations in the study as well
 as on 5 super populations and the study as a whole.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We discovered that there was great variation in the presence of cryptic
 relatedness and population structure across the 26 populations of the study.
 Under the assumptions that each study contained a homogeneous population
 of unrelated individuals, only a handful of groups contained neither large
 outliers nor heavily inflated numbers of significant results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We defined the presence of population structure as applying to those populations
 which had a median 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,j}<.97$
\end_inset

.
 Using this criterion, three of the 26 populations met this threshold- MXL
 (Mexican Ancestry from Los Angeles USA), PUR (Puerto Ricans from Puerto
 Rico), and PEL (Peruvians from Lima, Peru).
 Each of these populations are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 populations which have undergone extensive admixture in the past centuries.
 It is therefore unsurprising that these groups of individuals would exhibit
 the greatest amount of heterogeneity among the populations surveyed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We defined the presence of cryptic relatedness as those individual pairs
 which exceed the cutoff for a family-wise error rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=.01$
\end_inset

.
 Cryptic relatedness was discovered in 12 
\series bold
[update this with latest results]
\series default
 of the 26 populations using this method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overlap in these two groups may be due to the fact that the variance
 in similarity is inflated in the presence of population structure.
 So it is not accurate to identify cryptic relatedness in this manner in
 popultations which contain structure.
 However, in populations which do not exhibit detectable structure, we still
 find many instances of related individuals in this study.
 For example, two individuals from the ACB population (African Caribbeans
 in Barbados) had a 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 score of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.6$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p<10^{-30}\right)$
\end_inset

, whereas no other pairing exceeded the family-wise cutoff of 1.3 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p=.0002\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Using the formula above, we estimate this relationship to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi=X$
\end_inset

 [Redo this analysis], indicating...
\end_layout

