\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Presence of population structure and cryptic relatedness detected in each
 of the 26 populations in the 1000 Genomes Project.
 Population structure, defined as a 
\begin_inset Formula $median\left(s\right)<.97$
\end_inset

 was found in three groups- MXL, PEL and PUR.
 Each of these populations are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

new world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 populations which have undergone extensive admixture in the past centuries.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Population detection in 1000 Genomes Project
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are many methods for detecting population structure.
 Most commonly, Principal Components Analysis 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{price2006principal,price2010new}
\end_layout

\end_inset

is applied for identifying the components of largest variation which ideally
 corresponds to the population structure.
 This procedure first involves the calculation of a genetic similarity matrix
 (GSM) via the correlation between all samples, which is commonly followed
 by an eigendecomposition of that matrix.
 There are a number of limitations to this straightforward approach, one
 of which is that the calculation of a variance-covariance matrix equally
 weights the impact of all loci 
\series bold
[unless standardized by rows?]
\series default
, failing to fully utilize the fact that the overall allele frequency is
 informative of the value of each variant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used the 1000 Genomes Project data to compare the GSMs obtained via the
 conventional variance-covariance matrix step and the use of our method.
 We evaluated the ability of each method to separate the same quantity of
 data into the 5 superpopulations and 26 populations.
 Using approximately 80,000
\series bold
 [Adjust for filtered]
\series default
 variants, we generated the two GSMs and plotted the similarity matrices,
 ordered by hierarchical clustering with average linkage (Figure 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ref{fig:heatmaps}
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both methods performed well at separating the five superpopulations, but
 the our method outperformed variance covariance in separating populations
 of the same superpopulation.
 As expected, the lack of focus on less frequent alleles, which are more
 important for distinguishing recent ancestry allowed variance-covariance
 to adequately separate continental origins, but failed to sufficiently
 partition the samples according to subgroups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
A
\series default

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/dan/gd/Harvard/Research/R_workspace/Slides/pasted14.png
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\series bold
B
\series default

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/dan/gd/Harvard/Research/R_workspace/Slides/pasted15.png
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
C
\series default

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /home/dan/gd/Harvard/Research/R_workspace/Slides/pasted5.png
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Heatmap of GSM generated by our method (A) and variance-covariance (B) using
 80,000 uniformly spaced variants.
 Samples have been ordered by hierarchical clustering (dendrogram no shown).
 The vertical colorbar indicates membership in one of the five superpopulations,
 while the horizontal colorbar indicates membership in one of the 26 populations.
 (C) Projecting each individual onto the top two eigenvectors resulted in
 a similar 2-dimensional distribution of global ancestry
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
label{fig:heatmaps}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first two eigenvectors of the GSMs generated using our method vs variance-co
variance yield very similar results.
 Both methods provide a sufficient separation of coarse-scale population
 structure.
 But closer examination of fine-scale population structure reveals our method
 to be an improvement over variance-covariance.
 We were able to provide a stronger separation of all 26 populations, particular
ly those of recent ancestry.
 As an example, we explored two populations- Sri Lankan Tamil and Indian
 Telugu, which have relatively small geographical separation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interestingly, we found a strong case for cryptic relatedness between three
 pairs of individuals, one pair of which (HG03998 and HG03873) spanned the
 two populations.
 Considering that both groups were sampled in the UK, this suggests a distant
 genetic relationship is possible from members of different population groups.
\end_layout

